         <abstract>
            <p>The famous study by Ian Little entitled "Higgledy Piggledy Growth" concluded that "There is certainly no clear proof of any positive relation between past and future growth." The author tests this conclusion by ranking companies in categories according to their earnings growth rate in a five-year period and then examining the growth rate of each category during the subsequent five years. His study not only confirms the findings of Little but shows that, the higher the earnings gain in the former period, the lower the earnings gain in the latter--suggesting that there is no justification for basing the price of stock on past earnings growth.</p>
          </abstract>
